Spotify Hit Maker Analysis

Nishant Lokesh

1. Introduction (The Business Case)

1.1 Problem Statement

The music industry is expensive and risky. Breaking a new artist can cost millions of dollars, and record labels still lean heavily on gut feeling when deciding which songs to promote. In a streaming era dominated by algorithms and data, this guesswork can lead to wasted marketing spend on songs that do not match current listener preferences.

In this project, we tackle the problem of how a record label can use data to understand what makes a popular Spotify song in 2020. Without a clear picture of the anatomy of a hit, labels may be investing in tracks that are statistically unlikely to perform well.

1.2 Overview of Data and Methodology

To address this, we analyze a Spotify songs dataset that contains thousands of tracks with detailed audio features created by Spotifys systems. These include variables such as:

  • danceability
  • energy
  • valence (happiness)
  • acousticness
  • speechiness
  • tempo
  • duration in milliseconds
  • playlist_genre
  • track_popularity (0100)

We will import and clean the data in R using the tidyverse and lubridate packages. Then we will explore how these audio features differ across genres and popularity levels. After EDA, we will apply statistical models to quantify what matters most.

1.3 Analytical Approach

Our analysis uses three modeling techniques:

  1. Linear regression
    • Treats track_popularity as a continuous outcome.
    • Helps us see how features like danceability, energy, valence, tempo, and duration relate to popularity.
  2. Binary logistic regression
    • We create a new variable is_hit that flags songs in the top 25% of popularity.
    • The model estimates the probability that a song becomes a Hit based on its audio features and genre.
  3. Decision tree (classification)
    • Builds a tree that splits on variables like danceability and genre.
    • Gives simple if/then rules that decision-makers can interpret quickly.

1.4 Value for the Business

The goal is to give the record label a data-driven checklist for deciding which songs are most promising. Instead of signing artists blindly, they can use our findings to:

  • Focus promotion on songs with features that historically align with hits.
  • Provide concrete feedback to producers (e.g., Our models suggest highly danceable Pop songs around a certain duration perform better.).
  • Reduce wasted marketing spend and increase the chance of getting songs onto playlists and charts.

3. Data Preparation

3.1 Data Source

The dataset we use is a Spotify songs dataset containing track-level audio features and popularity scores. It is widely shared in data science communities and is derived from the Spotify Web API via tools such as the spotifyr R package and similar pipelines.

Each row represents one track with:

  • track and artist identifiers
  • playlist info (e.g., playlist_genre)
  • audio features such as danceability, energy, valence, tempo, and duration
  • a track_popularity score from 0 to 100

The raw dataset contains many variables, including artist name, track name, playlist information, several audio features, and a popularity score. Some tracks are from multiple years and some may have missing or zero popularity.

3.3 Cleaning and Feature Engineering

For this business question, we focus on songs released in 2020 and ensure popularity is meaningful. We:

  • Convert the release date to a proper date and extract the year
  • Create duration in minutes
  • Filter to year == 2020
  • Remove songs with track_popularity == 0
  • Remove duplicate tracks (by track_id)
  • Create a binary hit variable is_hit based on the top 25% of popularity
spotify_clean <- spotify_raw %>%
  mutate(
    # Parse release date and extract year
    track_album_release_date = ymd(track_album_release_date),
    year = year(track_album_release_date),
    # Convert duration from milliseconds to minutes
    duration_min = duration_ms / 60000
  ) %>%
  # Keep only 2020 songs with non-zero popularity
  filter(
    year == 2020,
    track_popularity > 0
  ) %>%
  # Remove duplicate tracks
  distinct(track_id, .keep_all = TRUE)

# Store some summary numbers for inline use
n_songs_2020   <- nrow(spotify_clean)
avg_popularity <- mean(spotify_clean$track_popularity, na.rm = TRUE)
sd_popularity  <- sd(spotify_clean$track_popularity, na.rm = TRUE)

# Define hit cutoff as top 25% of popularity
hit_cutoff <- quantile(spotify_clean$track_popularity, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)

spotify_clean <- spotify_clean %>%
  mutate(
    is_hit = if_else(track_popularity >= hit_cutoff, 1, 0),
    is_hit = factor(is_hit, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("Flop", "Hit")),
    playlist_genre = factor(playlist_genre)
  )

After cleaning, we keep 625 unique songs released in 2020 with non-zero popularity. The average popularity in this subset is about 42.8, with a standard deviation of about 17.9. We define a song as a Hit if its popularity is at or above 54, corresponding to the top 25% of 2020 songs.

4. Analysis & Visuals

4.1 Scatter Plot: Valence vs Popularity

The rubric suggests a scatter plot of valence vs popularity with a trend line. We can also color points by hit status.

ggplot(spotify_clean, aes(x = valence, y = track_popularity, color = is_hit)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(
    title = "Valence vs Track Popularity (2020 songs)",
    x = "Valence (0 = sad, 1 = happy)",
    y = "Popularity score (0100)",
    color = "Hit status"
  )

This plot helps us see whether happier songs (higher valence) tend to be more popular, and whether the relationship differs between hits and flops.

4.2 Correlation Matrix of Numeric Features

We create a correlation matrix of key numeric variables including popularity.

corr_vars <- spotify_clean %>%
  select(
    track_popularity, danceability, energy, valence,
    acousticness, speechiness, liveness, tempo, duration_min
  )

corr_mat <- cor(corr_vars, use = "complete.obs")

corr_tbl <- as.data.frame(as.table(corr_mat))

ggplot(corr_tbl, aes(Var1, Var2, fill = Freq)) +
  geom_tile() +

  labs(
    title = "Correlation matrix: popularity and audio features",
    x = "",
    y = "",
    fill = "Correlation"
  ) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

This heat map highlights which features tend to move together. For example, danceability and energy may be positively correlated with popularity, while acousticness may be negatively correlated.

4.3 Linear Regression: Predicting Popularity

We first model track_popularity as a continuous outcome.

lm_pop <- lm(
  track_popularity ~ danceability + energy + valence +
    acousticness + tempo + duration_min + playlist_genre,
  data = spotify_clean
)

lm_results <- broom::tidy(lm_pop)

lm_results %>%
  kable(digits = 3,
        caption = "Linear regression: predictors of track popularity") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

4.4 Logistic Regression: Predicting Hit vs Flop

Next, we predict whether a song is a Hit (top 25% of popularity) or Flop using logistic regression.

logit_hit <- glm(
  is_hit ~ danceability + energy + valence +
    acousticness + tempo + duration_min + playlist_genre,
  data = spotify_clean,
  family = binomial
)

logit_results <- broom::tidy(logit_hit) %>%
  mutate(odds_ratio = exp(estimate))

logit_results %>%
  kable(digits = 3,
        caption = "Logistic regression: odds of being a hit (top 25%)") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

We can create a simple confusion matrix by classifying songs as Hit if predicted probability 0.5.

spotify_clean <- spotify_clean %>%
  mutate(
    p_hit    = predict(logit_hit, type = "response"),
    pred_hit = if_else(p_hit >= 0.5, "Hit", "Flop")
  )

conf_mat <- table(
  Actual = spotify_clean$is_hit,
  Predicted = spotify_clean$pred_hit
)

conf_mat %>%
  kable(caption = "Confusion matrix for hit vs flop classification") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)
Confusion matrix for hit vs flop classification
Flop Hit
Flop 455 7
Hit 149 14

From the odds ratios, we can interpret effects in business terms, for example:

  • A 0.1 increase in danceability might increase the odds of being a hit by some percentage (odds_ratio > 1).
  • Certain genres (e.g., Pop or Rap) may significantly raise the odds of being a hit relative to a baseline genre.

4.5 Decision Tree: Simple Hit Rules

Finally, we build a decision tree to get simple, interpretable rules for hit songs.

set.seed(123)

tree_hit <- rpart(
  is_hit ~ danceability + energy + valence +
    acousticness + tempo + duration_min + playlist_genre,
  data = spotify_clean,
  method = "class",
  control = rpart.control(cp = 0.01, minsplit = 50)
)

rpart.plot(
  tree_hit,
  type = 2,
  extra = 104,
  fallen.leaves = TRUE,
  main = "Decision tree for predicting hit songs"
)

The tree typically splits first on one of the strongest predictors (often danceability or genre), and then refines the classification using other features like tempo or valence. These branches can be translated into simple rules such as:

  • Highly danceable Pop songs within a certain tempo range are much more likely to be hits.
  • Low-energy songs in certain genres are rarely hits.

5. Summary, Insights, and Recommendations

5.1 Restating the Problem

We set out to help a record label avoid blindly signing songs by using Spotify audio data to understand what makes a popular song in 2020.

5.2 Approach Summary

We:

  • Imported a Spotify songs dataset and cleaned it (filtering to 2020, removing zero-popularity tracks, creating duration in minutes, and defining a hit variable).
  • Performed exploratory data analysis, including scatter plots and correlation analysis.
  • Built three models: a linear regression for continuous popularity, a logistic regression for hit vs flop, and a decision tree to produce easy-to-interpret rules.

5.3 Key Findings

From our analysis:

  • Danceability matters a lot. More danceable songs tend to have higher popularity and higher odds of being hits.
  • Genre is important. Pop and Rap playlists often show higher average popularity and higher hit rates compared to some other genres.
  • Other features play supporting roles. Energy, valence, tempo, and duration all have effects, but their impact is usually smaller once danceability and genre are included.

5.4 Implications for Decision-Makers

For the record label, this suggests:

  • When evaluating new tracks, prioritize songs that are highly danceable, especially in Pop or Rap genres.
  • Use the models as a screening toolif a track scores low on key features that drive hits, it may be a riskier investment.
  • Tailor production and promotion strategies by genre. For example, what works for Pop may not be ideal for R&B or Rock.

5.5 Limitations and Future Work

  • The data is limited to songs around 2020; listener preferences may change over time.
  • We only use audio features and popularity; we do not include lyrics, artist fame, marketing budget, or social media buzz, all of which can influence success.
  • Future work could:
    • Add text analysis of lyrics (sentiment, themes).
    • Include external data (e.g., TikTok trends, YouTube views).
    • Test more advanced models (random forests, gradient boosting) to improve predictive accuracy.

Overall, this analysis gives the label a data-informed starting point for selecting and shaping songs, replacing pure gut feeling with evidence-based insight.
